f the contemporary questions concerning realism and antirealism. . . . Clear, thoughtful, [and] well-written."—Allan Franklin, Annals of Science "Attempts, from Einstein's published works and unpublished correspondence, to piece together a coherent picture of 'Einstein realism.' Especially illuminating are the letters between Einstein and fellow realist Schrödinger, as the latter was composing his famous 'Schrödinger-Cat' paper."—Nick Herbert, New Scientist "Beautifully clear. . . . Fine's analysis is penetrating, his own results original and important. . . . The book is a splendid combination of new ways to think about quantum mechanics, about realism, and about Einstein's views of both."—Nancy Cartwright, Isis  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPhysicsxPhilosophy. 0aQuantum theory. 0aRealism. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aquantum mechanics, realism, antirealism, science, einstein, schrodinger, physics, philosophy, truth, uncertainty, completeness, prism models, probability, quarks, positivism, nonfiction, empiricism, determinism, bohr, momentum, epr, schrodingers cat, unknowability, epistemology, universe, natural laws, discovery, innovation, research, reality, sensory perception.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226923260423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226923260/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles